          <td valign="top" width="1" ><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="18" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td  valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <BR><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="4ef0d8bcf9aa9f741a2cc972c1dbb32e" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr height="10"><td width="98%" bgcolor="#333333" height="10"><img src="/magic/gfx/trans.gif" width="6" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td><td valign="bottom" align="right"><img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/tk.gif" width="103" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr><tr><td>&nbsp;</td><td valign="top" align="right">
<img src="/magic/gfx/hrz/bk.gif" width="92" height="24" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td>
</tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Power of Black<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magic/gfx/star2.gif" width="20" height="20" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.71)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=6207'>Patrick "Wittens Hand" Dennis</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=6207&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 31, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Black, we&#39;ve all seen this color and we all shudder when we think about it. What is it about this color that makes it so powerful? Yes, it has its drawbacks, but it also has some great strengths. I will show you the strengths then show you the weaknesses.<br />
<br />
The first strength of black is that it can instantly kill most creatures. This indiscriminate killing helps as opposed to red that has very few outright destroy target creature spells. Black will kill almost anything but black, but also has a little trouble with artifacts.<br />
<br />
We have all seen Black*s destructive potential. The ability to destroy a creature regardless its toughness is a great tool. It also shows one of Black*s weaknesses to be described later.<br />
<br />
The second strength of black is that it can discard cards from people*s hands. This allows black to get around its own weaknesses by getting rid of them before they enter play. Most discards are sorceries, but there is one or two instant discard abilities. The most notable one is Greel Mindraker. For five mana two of which is black you get a 3/3 with the ability of paying BxT, Discard two cards from your hand: Target player discards x cards from their hand.<br />
<br />
This is probably the one place black excels from the others. Blue has some limited discard, but nothing nearly like black.<br />
<br />
The third strength of Black is its ability to manipulate the graveyard. Every other color has very limited manipulation. Black can either get a creature on top of their deck, in their hand, or directly back into play. That ability alone can win games as you get one of blacks many different huge creatures into play quickly. Green may have mana acceleration, but black&#8217;s ability to go toe to toe with green by sacrificing its own creatures in suicide runs, and then bring them back for more is incredible. Only red has as much destructive potential this way in sacrificing creatures. But red also can&#8217;t get back what it loses.<br />
<br />
The fourth strength of Black is its ability to cause a swing in life. This swing is the ability to do damage then gain life equal to that damage. This is actually powerful as when you bring them down five or six life, and then gain five or six life the difference becomes ten or twelve life. Making it much harder to close the gap and even harder to survive. I*ll list three different cards and point out strengths and weaknesses of such cards.<br />
<br />
3BB Subversion<br />
Enchantment<br />
During your upkeep each player loses 1 life. For each 1 life lost gain 1 life.<br />
<br />
Obvious in its abilities, you plop this down and the game starts getting shorter for your opponents. This card excels in multiplayer games. The downfalls are simple however. Unless you get multiple copies out, in a single-player you wont deal enough damage to stay alive for long against speed green and such. Also white will trash this little rare from Urza*s Saga with a ten cents common called Disenchant. Blue can counter it before it gets in play, red can deal direct damage with blazing speed to make sure your new gain in life isn*t worth much. Black will have a slight problem with it, but might counter with a massive horde of creatures. Then finish you off quick.<br />
<br />
1B Drain Life<br />
Sorcery<br />
For each B you spend in addition to the casting cost, deal 1 damage to your opponent. Gain 1 life for each damage dealt. If you drain life from a creature you can&#8217;t gain life more than it&#8217;s toughness.<br />
<br />
OK, it&#8217;s the black fireball Drain Life. This card has versatility in allowing you to use it in the first few turns of the game. Most players use this in a combo with infinite mana to kill other players, but its good on its own. The drawbacks are simple, you must spend mana to gain life, and what you spend to cast it initially doesn&#8217;t count. If you plan on playing any other spells that turn, you will not gain life for the untapped swamps. On top of that it diminishes its effectiveness, and makes you extremely susceptible to a power sink later on.<br />
5B Corrupt<br />
Sorcery<br />
Corrupt deals 1 damage to target creature or player for each swamp you control. If corrupt successfully deals damage to a creature or player, gain that much life.<br />
<br />
This is my favorite card for the job. Its strengths are that it&#8217;s a fixed amount of mana for an absurd amount of damage. Since you don&#8217;t have to tap mana for additional damage you can cast other spells, as long as you ration mana accordingly. The only problem with this card is you must wait for six mana to use it. This can be tedious, as you will be tinkering with smaller mana spells to hold them off. Additionally, rethink can kill this card making you pay its casting cost again to keep it in play.<br />
<br />
Which leads me to Black*s weaknesses. It has very little in the ways of enchantment destruction. This means that if you drop something like contemplation or even something like Smoldering Tar, black has very little in the ways of getting rid of such problems. Couple it with Blue or White and you stand a chance there.<br />
<br />
Another weakness of black is itself. Black decks featuring creature destruction (like my deck Woe) will have problems killing black creatures. To avoid this, play blue with its color changing spells to get rid of them. A sway of illusion can turn their black creatures killable and fair game to your black spells. Just be careful that blue doesn&#8217;t copy this tactic and change its stuff black to stop your spell making it fizzle as you wonder why it had to happen.<br />
<br />
Probably a big weakness that is a weakness to all decks is counters. Black has no way to combat counters other than flooding spells through. So unless they can counter it all, you will kill them. Standard practice is to hold two spells, then cast them both one after the other. Make both spells a pain in their side, and hope they counter what you don&#8217;t want to allow what you do want in play.<br />
<br />
This concludes my article. Tell me what you think and leave all donations to me at the door. J/K!<br />
